author: suchow
message:
Fix bug in waiting for Redis (#329)

To check if the Redis queue is available, we try to write to it.
However, sometimes the URL for the Redis queue is not immediately
available. The existing implementation retrieves this URL once and then
pings it over and over. The new implementation retrieves the URL once
per ping. Thus it is updated as soon as the URL becomes available,
preventing an infinite hang.

author: davisagli
message:
Misc improvements to testing infrastructure: (#340)

- Run coverage as a wrapper of nosetests rather than using nosetest's coverage plugin.
  This fixes a problem where completely uncovered files were not reported.
- Make the build fail if coverage is under a threshold (currently 30%; we can increase it over time).
- Set up tox and make travis run tox.
  This makes it easier to run the same tests locally that are run by Travis.
- Use Travis' matrix feature to run tests in parallel with building docs.
- Add documentation about running tests
- Add missing documentation about installing the pandoc dependency
- Add a few missing words to the spelling list
- Add command to run flake8 (but don't run it automatically yet; I'll add that in a separate pull request once I've fixed the errors)

author: silviot
message:
Do not capture stdout/stderr during docker test runs

It's very useful to be able to see the timestamp github actions
provide for each line in the log, to reason about how the timeouts
impacted on the test.
pytest by default swallows all output during test runs.
Adding `-s` shows the output as they are run, instead of in a single
block after they run.

Integrate with the Open Science Framework (#432)

Dallinger now integrates with the Open Science Framework (OSF),
creating a new OSF project and uploading experiment code to the project

in your .dallingerconfig file. You can generate a new OSF personal
access token on the OSF settings page.

author: pmcharrison
message:
Minor update to network visualistion (#3932)

I have fixed a couple of small formatting issues with the dashboard network visualisation.

First, I have updated the text by Infos so that it says the class name rather than just 'info'. This is particularly useful for PsyNet, where the term 'Info' is not so informative.

Second, I have fixed an issue for the display of networks that have no nodes; previously the visualization would draw a line between these networks and an unrelated node from a different network. Now the network is just left without any connections.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Attempt to open experiment with clean profiles

The webbrowser module has implementations for opening windows in
common browsers, with the correct command line flags to open new
windows or new tabs. This checks if Chrome or Firefox is installed
and if so instantiates a new browser control that opens a new profile
using a temporary directory. If neither are available it falls back
to the ordering in webbrowser, so users who don't have Chrome or FF
see the existing behaviour.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Update quorum channel when generating status report

When running an experiment the controlling process periodically
requests a status report. This suborns that mechanism to also
publish periodic updates on the state of the quorum. This prevents
bots who lose their connection to the quorum channel over the critical
point of quorum being reached from being stuck in the waiting room.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Add realtime playback functionality

This adds a button to the `jupyter_replay` widget that attempts to replay
the experiment in real-time. It advances the current state in a loop
controlled by a thread. At the end of each iteration the amount of wall
time that has passed is used to determine the next state to restore up to.
A thread is used to ensure the kernel remains responsive, allowing the user
to pause the replay, which causs the thread to error out.

author: suchow
message:
Use random bits to form UUID

The default behavior of `uuid.uuid4()` uses random bits generated by the OS and is thus unresponsive to seeding the random number generator. Here, we generate the UUID using 128 pseudorandom bits. This helps with computational reproducibility.

string. Decode to utf-8 so the socket implementation can correctly encode
this for transmission to the user.

Add HighPerformanceBots framework

This is an alternative implementation of the BaseBot that experiments
may subclass that attempts to keep the same signature but uses
python-requests to set up the participant instead of a selenium
testbrowser. This makes the bots more light-weight and removes
the dependency on a browser.

Lint commit messages (#344)

Danger now warns if any of these style guidelines are violated:

- Commit subject begins with a capital letter (subject_cap)
- Commit subject is no longer than 50 characters (subject_length)
- Commit subject does not end in a period (subject_period)
- Commit subject and body are separated by an empty line (empty_line)

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Tox should use development mode installations

Note, the following contains supposition:

Tox uses sdists to install the package under test, but now we have a
pytest plugin our code is loaded earlier than test discovery, which
is too early for the path it's installed under to be whitelisted
by the coverage plugin.

This change instructs tox to use a development install instead, so
a direct link with the files on disk is used.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Make get_base_url calls return a random valid port locally

Although you can increase the number of web dynos locally, only once will get the configured port, this change uses num_dynos_web to determine the maximum port that can be used locally and picks a random port for that range. In addition, it calls get_base_url every time a new bot is created, not just the first time. This approximately load balances the bots on web servers.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Wrap subprocess calls to redirect to nonfunctional std streams

Under Jupyter the stderr and stdout streams do not have file numbers,
so the subprocess family of calls cannot write to them directly. This
wraps these calls with a method to detect when calls do not specify
redirection of these streams and if it detects a nonfunctional output
it uses a temporary file and reads the data afterwards.

This causes output under Jupyter to be slower at updating than on
the command line, but allows for experiments to be run.

author: suchow
message:
Handle optional --app flags

Commands such as `dallinger sandbox` and `dallinger deploy` have
optional `--app` flags, which should be verified only if provided. On
the other hand, commands such as `dallinger summary` have mandatory
`--app` flags. This change puts each command in the proper category.

message:
Upgrade docker compose to v2 (#4976)

Upgrade docker compose to v2:
* Update dependencies; remove pin from sphinx; replace recommonmark with myst-parser
* Remove docker-compose (v1) package
* Use 'yaml.safe_load'
* Migrate 'docker-compose' to 'docker compose' 
* Replace '_' with '-' in container names
* Fix COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME
* Remove compose file format version from yml files

---------

Co-authored-by: Frank Höger <frank.hoeger@ae.mpg.de>

author: suchow
message:
Wait after recruitment is complete

In some experiments, the experiment becomes complete the moment the
final participant submits their HIT, setting their status away from
`working`. Sometimes there is so little time between when the
experiment becomes complete and the server is shut off that the server
becomes unavailable *during* the interchange when the final bot
participant submits the questionnaire, leaving them unable to finish.
This change adds the delay before ever checking whether the experiment
is complete.

author: suchow
message:
Simplify configuration API naming (#495)

* Rename config.load_from_config_file()

`config.load_from_config_file()` => `config.load_from_file()`

* Rename config.write_config()

`config.write_config()` => `config.write()`

* Rename config.load_config()

`config.load_config()` => `config.load()`

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Support Selenium drivers other than local PhantomJS

This change allows users to specify the webdriver_url configuration parameter, which points at a Selenium Server, such as http://192.168.1.2:4444/wd/hub. If this is specified the webdriver.Remote backend is used.
In addition, webdriver_type determines the browser being used. If a URL is specified these are passed as desired_capabilities to the hub server, otherwise it is used to pick a local webdriver. Currently supported values are 'phantomjs' and 'firefox'.

author: silviot
message:
Pin Flask<2.0

We currently depend on sphinx-js for our documentation, which in turn specifies
Jinja2>2.0,<3.0
as a dependency. The new Flask 2.0 (released in May 2021) depends on Jinja>=3.

Ideally the dependencies we use to generate documentation should not impact the ones
used to run a web server, but for now they do.
Also upgrading to Flask 2.0 might require significant effort.

author: suchow
message:
Fix sort order issue in MCMCP demo

When running a long chain, @jcpeterson noticed that every so often the
mapping between the "left" and "right" buttons flipped. The error was
non-deterministic and hard to predict. After a long debugging session,
we realized that the order of infos returned by the
`node/<node_id>/infos` route is non-deterministic (or at least not
always sequential in node id). This is a fix that behaves properly no
matter what order the returned infos are sorted in.

Closes #570.

Be quieter about invalid configuration keys

keys for Dallinger's configuration. Rather than spew a list of these
each time an experiment is run, default to being quiet about this
unless the logger level is set to debug. On the other hand, if the user
includes an invalid configuration variable in a config file, then it
makes sense to complain.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Move experiment qualification to after waiting room

If an experiment is overrecruiting then the experiment qualification
should only be given to users who are actually shown the experiment.
If someone joins then is discarded by the waiting room they should
be unqualified. Assigning then removing the qualification causes
spurious emails to be generated by MTurk, so we change the way
overrecruitment is defined to be a python function rather than
comparing two elements of a JSON value in Javascript. This lets
us assign the qualification in Python code and makes for a slightly
more standardised override story for experimenters.

author: thomasmorgan
message:
Improve participant management

- worker_id must be unique
- attempt to duplicate participant returns existing participant
- cannot create participant with same worker_id, but different
assignment_id. Returns error.
- assignment_id can be reused by different participants
- creating a participant with a non-unique assignment id marks other
participants with that assignment_id as replaced
- remove old function check_for_duplicate_assignments, this is now
handled at participant creation, not by notification receipt
- notifications are always assumed to apply to the most recent
participant
- new participant status “replaced” for when assignment_ids are
reassigned
- new experiment method exp.assignment_reassigned to handle assignment
reassignment, by default it fails the participant

author: fmhoeger
message:
Remove deprecation warnings and update mentions of Python versions (#5196)

* Get rid of distutils
* Migrate 'pkg_resources import iter_entry_points' to 'importlib.metadata import entry_points'
* Drop leftovers of support for Python 3.7 (importlib_metadata); Remove all mentions of Python 3.7; update all Python version occurences to 3.8, 3.9, and 3.10
* Add 'from dallinger import experiments'
* Add python3.10 to docker volumes
* Fix getting entry_points for Python3.8 and 3.9
* Remove pkg_resources.require
* Remove dallinger.utils.pkg_resources mock.patch from test
* Upgrade .readthedocs.yml to Python 3.10
* Switch to 'find_namespace_packages' for adding the 'dlgr.demos' namespace
* Fix 'DeprecationWarning: use options instead of chrome_options'
* Load enty points using 'importlib.metadata' instead of 'pkg_resources' in ci.yml
* Fix 'DeprecationWarning: use options instead of chrome_options'

---------

Co-authored-by: Frank Höger <frank.hoeger@ae.mpg.de>

author: silviot
message:
Use the current dallinger version's requirements.txt to constaint te `generate-constraints` command

The `generate-constraints` command should make sure the version it produces (especially those for
packages that require compilation, like psycopg) match the ones bundled in the docker image for
the dallinger version the package is pinned for.

This commit makes dallinger use the current (CLI) version for itself, and the requirements.txt file
that was produced for that version and used to build the corresponding docker image.

message:
Add a consent route (#223)

Dallinger v2.3.0 unintentionally shipped with a breaking change.
Because routes no longer automatically rendered with the four
parameters in the query string that were hardcoded in psiTurk (hid_id,
assignment_id, worker_id, and mode), the consent forms all became
broken. This fixes the problem so that now the old demos still work.

author: pmcharrison
message:
Misc Docker quality of life improvements (#4616)

# Major

- Disabled the behavior where the built image name is written to config.txt. This behavior was inconsistent with the other Dallinger deployment patterns, because it meant that if you deployed once, changed code in experiment.py, then redeployed, then the experiment would launch in the former version unless you remembered to delete the image name from config.txt.
- Heroku deployments were failing because the default `heroku_python_version` had been discontinued by Heroku. We have experienced similar problems in the past and have always had to update Dallinger. Now we have changed the behaviour such that, if `heroku_python_version` is not specified in the experiment config, then it will use the default Python runtime currently in use by Heroku.

# Minor

- Propagate more information from deployment-related functions (e.g. dashboard credentials) so that they can be used by wrapper functions.
- Print more information (e.g. dashboard credentials) in deployment-related functions.
- Better debugging logs for docker-ssh deployments.
- Move deployment info logs from `deployment-info_{experiment_id}.txt` to `deploy_logs/*` to avoid clutter.
- Move default `dallinger_develop_directory` to `/tmp/dallinger_develop` because the original location was not writable by default on Docker.
- Minor bugfixes in docker-ssh deployment/export.
- Rename config variable `docker_ssh_volumes` -> `docker_volumes` because it's relevant also when we're doing docker locally. 
- Some minor renaming of internal variables for consistency.

author: suchow
message:
Load configuration even without local config.txt

Previously, when a local config.txt cannot be found in the current
working directory, a value error is raised. This change allows the
configuration to load even when there is no such config.txt, which
makes it possible to use to configuration even outside the context of
an experiment directory (e.g., to get AWS keys to load data from S3 in
an analysis script).

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Special case MacOS when opening new Chrome browsers

MacOS uses applescript to open its browsers as the Chrome (and other)
executables aren't in PATH. If the end user didn't set PATH to include
the MacOS subdirectory of the application package then opening a new
chrome would fall back to the webbrowser applescript method which
would not cause a new profile to be created.

This checks for the presence of the Chrome package (with a config
override for location) and uses that path on darwin in it is found.

author: MatthewWilkes
message:
Patch jupyter output stream

The ipykernel's implementation of iostream marks files as not writable. This makes
some sense, as they do not implement `fileno\(\)`, so can't be written by `os.write\(\)`
but it can cause libraries like pexpect to refuse to write data directly, which
still works. This patch overrides the value, and we will handle the special-casing
in different commits.
